<section type="Titlepage">

A DICTIONARIE FRENCH AND ENGLISH.</heading> <heading><term lang="la">ANNO DO. M.D.LXXI.</term>
</heading>

<page sig="[*]2v">

<page sig="[*]2r">
<section type="Dedication">
<heading>
To the Reader.
</heading>
BLinde Bayarde is boldest to
launch into the deepe, and
rashe Souldiour readiest to
giue the first assault: Though wilful
blindnesse, and headdy rashnesse be 
vices intolerable, yet suche blinde&shy;
nesse and suche rashenesse (in my
iudgement) is c<expan type="o+_">om</expan>mendable, as either
breaketh the yce vnto the better see&shy;
ing, or treadeth the path to the discret 
and cunning. This perswasion hath
made me presume to Englishe this
worke: and this mine onset hereafter
may prouoke the skilfull to perfit
the same. In the mean while (good Rea&shy;
der) vse it to thy profit, so shalt thou
encourage me (according to my skill
and leasure) to further thy studies.
L. H.
</section>


</page>

</page>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="fr">A</form> <xpln lang="en">The first letter serueth many ti&shy;
mes to expresse the Datiue case:
as, <term lang="fr">Ie l'ay donn&eacute; &agrave; mon pere.</term> I 
gaue it to my father: Sometime it serueth for the preposition, To: as, 
<term lang="fr">Ie m'en vay &agrave; mon pere</term>, I go to my father.</xpln></wordentry>
